<font color="#FF0000">REPLIES</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 10 17:24:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur-historical muckraking does no one any good. I wrote alot of posts &quot;before&quot; I began to rethink. Some of them I wish I hadn't written, now, but I can live with it. Throwing my past back in the present serves nobody any good now, unless you wish to point out how closed minded a &quot;lefty&quot; or resistor could be, same as a veteran or a conservative.  The image you see of a circle, a snake eating its own tail. I see more of a endless spiral, slowing growing upward, endlessly learning. Pehaps you hold me to standards that I can not match? I have no shingle to hang in this site, no active combat experiences (unless fighting rednecks to keep from getting a hair cut counts), and nothing to compare with the sacrafices and death you guys faced.  While I still believe absolutely that THAT war was wrong, I do not belittle you the experience, the survival, but I feel also, in my own heart, that I heard the siren song of my country call me too, and I did not flee, I stood my ground in my way, not as a soldier, not as a draft evader, but as an objector. (The three are very different - and I hope you will realize that).<br><br>
Edmond - Man, it must be those exhaust fumes that those slow Fords put out, that leak through the floor boards, that helped you create perhaps the most difficult questions I have ever been asked on this site: &quot;how did I decide to not march off to war?&quot;  <br><br>
I can't answer you this minute. I want to think about that. I remember standing up to my draft board, facing either civilian service if I &quot;won&quot; or 5 years at hard labor if I lost, was one of the scariest days/moments/minutes/eternities of my life. How I got there took several years, and I want to shift my brain (or what's left of it) back into replay for awhile and retrace my steps before I post a full answer.<br><br>
I can tell you this much. It was not a thing about guns or the taking of lives. I love to shoot and have a full gun locker. I do not think all wars are wrong. Some if not most wars were justified over history. If America was attacked I would be running to the front line without hesistation.<br><br>
Legally, if you have access to the archives of the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals, it was written up as #72-1775, Barry C. Spatz v. USA, Veterans Admin, City of Long Beach, et al. The openning brief's cover hangs in a frame on my wall in my den. It looks so odd to see my name versus this long list (about 4 inches) of governmental agencies and individuals, all because I did not think the war in Viet Nam was right.  How I got there, from being the patriotic kid with brand new draft card 4-5 years earlier, I don't know exactly?  Man, I just might have to write a novel to answer that.  But I will try in a latter, and briefer, post.  As to doubts about what I did, no Ed, I never had any because I always believed that if I went to Viet Nam I would come home in a bag.  Call it a premonition or a hunch, I don't know, I just always knew that deep down in my soul.  <br><br>
Enough for now, got to go polish my drag stip trophies.<br><br>
doc spatz
